            <div type="commentary">
                <head>Commentary</head>
                <list type="witDetail">
                    <item n="1"><p>MacNeill <ref type="bibliog"
                        target="#MAC1931"><bibl>(<date when="1931"
                            >1931</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >51</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> sugested an identification of ADDILONA with a mid-sixth-century <hi rend="italic">Siadliu</hi>, son of <hi rend="italic">Ferb</hi> and greatgrandfather of <hi rend="italic">Mo Chutu</hi>. 
                        However, <ref type="bibliog"
                            target="#MCM1991"><bibl><author>McManus</author> (<date when="1991"
                                >1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                    >172, note 25</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> pointed out that <q>the Kilbonane stone (241) presents a number of difficulties which MacNeill attempted to solve in his discussion ... Bergin  <ref type="bibliog"
                                        target="#BER1932"><bibl>(<date when="1932"
                                            >1932</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                                >107-11</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> rejected most of MacNeill's proposals including his 
                                        explanation of ADDILONA, pointing out that *<hi rend="italic">Saidliu</hi> is a phantom, the correct form of the name, in the genitive, being <hi rend="italic">Saiglenn</hi> with -g- not -d-. The loss of an initial S on the inscription would be exceptional</q>.</p></item>
                        
                        <item n="1"><p>In Macalister's view <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945"><bibl> 
                        (<date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                            >237</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>, <q>the only reasonable interpretation for this inscription [on the face of the stone] so far offered is that of Prof. MacNeill <ref type="bibliog"
                                target="#MAC1931"><bibl>(<date when="1931"
                                    >1931</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                        >53</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> (who reads the cryptical letters ABBA - <hi rend="italic">Ni raba amne dagni essi conidd ala amit 
                                            Baidagni</hi>: `let it not be thus he makes it, but let him compose it thus, `Baidagni'</q>. This interpretation was also rejected by Bergin <ref type="bibliog"
                                                target="#BER1932"><bibl>(<date when="1932"
                                                    >1932</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                                        >110</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> (see <ref
                                                            target="http://titus.fkidg1.uni-frankfurt.de/ogam/frame.htm"
                                                            >Gippert</ref>, CIIC 241, for details of these discussions). 
                         </p></item>
                </list>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="locations">
                <head>Locations</head>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Found</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="found">covering a vault beneath the E window inside the church ruin at <placeName
                            type="townland">Kilbonane</placeName> in the barony of <placeName
                                type="barony">Magunihy</placeName> (<ref type="bibliog" target="#BRA1879"
                                        ><bibl><author>Brash</author> <date when="1879"
                                            >1879</date>, <biblScope>234</biblScope></bibl></ref>) (GPS coordinates
                            <geo>-9.668483, 52.084366</geo>). </rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Original</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="origLocation">Unknown</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Last Recorded</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="lastLocation">In a small modern enclosure in <placeName
                            type="townland">Coolmagort</placeName> (together with the seven stones from a souterrain in that townland) near the entrance to the Gap of Dunloe. 
                            The present location of this stone may be accessed via the <ref
                                target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=KE065-078009-"
                                >National Monuments Service Historic Environment viewer on
                                www.archaeology.ie</ref>. (GPS coordinates
                            <geo>-9.634923, 52.06042</geo>)</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="record">
                <head>History of Recording</head>
                <p>Reported to have been discovered by R. Hitchcock and visited by Brash in August 1869 (<ref type="bibliog" target="#BRA1879"
                    ><bibl><author>Brash</author> <date when="1879"
                        >1879</date>, <biblScope>234</biblScope></bibl></ref>). By the time of <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945"><bibl><author>Macalister</author> 
                            (<date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >235</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> the stone had been moved to Coolmagort. <ref
                                    target="http://titus.fkidg1.uni-frankfurt.de/ogam/frame.htm"
                                    >Gippert</ref> noted that <q>it was lying prostrate when the site was visited in 1978 and 1981, 
                                    but had been erected leaning against a concrete pillar before 1998</q>.
                    </p>
            </div>
